INSERT INTO detail (id, title, detail, url, sequence) VALUES (16, 2, 'Why not separate out Old, Middle, and New kingdom as three separate “events”?  This is very tempting, and would be “better” in many ways.  For these ancient civilizations, there’s sufficient evidence for dates like this (c.3100 BC) corresponding to early civilization, and it seems meaningful to treat the Sumerians, Egyptians, and Indus civilizations (and early Huang He River civilization?) similarly, identifying them by their early city-states and signs of civilization, even before their first “kingdoms”, “dynasties”, or “empires”.  But hereafter, we focus on pivotal events or kingdoms, getting away from the more nebulous history.  E.g., we might focus on the Hyksos role marking the end of the Middle Kingdom c.1700.  So, rather than naming the Old Kingdom as the first instance of Egyptians, coming in closer to 2700 BC, we’ll stick with 3100 BC.', NULL, 1);
INSERT INTO detail (id, title, detail, url, sequence) VALUES (17, 2, 'Yes, Egyptians are extant today. However, 331 BC is seen to mark the end of the ancient culture of Egypt, as distinctive, when Alexander the Great conquerors Egypt, after it had already fallen to the Persians a decade earlier. Subsequently, Egypt remained Egypt in name and culture, and has a vivid history, but typically as a conquest of an empire such as the Roman Empire (30 BCE-476 CE) and the Byzantine Empire (c. 527-646 CE).  Beware that the grandest pyramids and the office of “pharaoh” are associated with later, “New Kingdom” Egyptians, not those that date back to 3100 BC.
